= Frederick Douglass

Frederick Douglass is the most prominent Black leader in America, a former enslaved man who became the nation's most powerful abolitionist voice, a celebrated author, and a tireless advocate for Black civil and political rights. His support for the Republican Party is genuine but not unconditional: he watches carefully to see whether the party's actions match its rhetoric. His moral authority among the freedmen community is without parallel.

